{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17649569","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17649569"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:04:58+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:04:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18367"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18367","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18367"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11085"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74385"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11085","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11085"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18367"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59876"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4899"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7418"},{"type":"tags","id":"7465"},{"type":"tags","id":"7466"},{"type":"tags","id":"11447"},{"type":"tags","id":"11448"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25707"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25709"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74385","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74385"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary function of the cuboid bone in the foot?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Forms the ankle joint with the tibia and fibula","Acts as a pulley for the flexor hallucis longus tendon","Provides stability to the lateral side of the foot","Facilitates dorsiflexion of the ankle","Supports the medial longitudinal arch"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe cuboid is one of the seven tarsal bones in the foot, located on the lateral side. It articulates with the calcaneus proximally and the fourth and fifth metatarsals distally.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe primary function of the cuboid bone is to \u003Cstrong\u003Eprovide stability to the lateral side of the foot\u003C/strong\u003E. It is a key component in maintaining the integrity of the lateral longitudinal arch.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESupports the medial longitudinal arch\u003C/strong\u003E - This is primarily the role of the navicular and cuneiform bones\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFacilitates dorsiflexion of the ankle\u003C/strong\u003E - This action involves the talus and the tibia and fibula\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EActs as a pulley for the flexor hallucis longus tendon\u003C/strong\u003E - The sustentaculum tali of the calcaneus serves this function\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EForms the ankle joint with the tibia and fibula\u003C/strong\u003E - The talus is the bone that articulates with the tibia and fibula to form the ankle joint\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The cuboid bone is one of the tarsal bones located in the foot.","The primary function of the cuboid bone is to provide stability to the lateral side of the foot.","The cuboid bone plays a role in the formation of the lateral longitudinal arch of the foot."],"references":["Patton, K. T., \u0026 Thibodeau, G. A. (2018). Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book: Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Smith, R., \u0026 Wordsworth, P. (2016). Oxford textbook of clinical and biochemical disorders of the skeleton. Oxford University Press","Sud, A., \u0026 Ranjan, R. (2021). Textbook of Orthopaedics, 2e-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Dandy, D. J., \u0026 Edwards, D. J. (2009). Essential Orthopaedics and Trauma E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","MacGregor R, Byerly DW. Anatomy, Bony Pelvis and Lower Limb: Foot Bones. 2023 May 23. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 32491379"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59876"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18367"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59876","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/59876"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-25T05:00:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-24T09:39:23+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11085"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74385"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"typ